Rudy,

    [Nobody else has responded to my note so I guess I'll play my
own devil's advocate.]

    I really don't care about "garbage" in the cache.  First of all
any .IL RR is correct (so not clearly garbage) and second, we can
make the ttl so short that the amount of time they will clutter up
your cache is tiny.

    As for waiting for days to find out that you sent to the wrong
host, I agree with you.  But it is a fact of life for a good bit
of the mail I send thru relays to USENET and BITNET (and other
people see it thru CSNET), and I'll be surprised if we completely
solve this problem with domains.  I also worry about maintaining
the fantasy that it will be possible to validate EVERY host name
under domains (what about those backwaters of the Usenet -- you think
a USENET server will be able to always stay current?).  Is
it so horrible to perpetuate the current practices?

    [Enough playing the devil]

Craig Partridge
CSNET Technical Staff

craig@csnet-sh (CSNET)
craig@loki (ARPA)
